@node "Menus" "Control Panel Guide - Menus"
@{b}@{u}Pull Down Menus@{ub}@{uu}

Control Panel 5 has a series of menus, most of which also appear as buttons,
and all include a hotkey which can be used to run that option.

The options that do not appear as buttons are as follows

@{fg shine}@{b}@{u}PROJECT@{uu}@{ub}@{fg text}

About - Version and Contact Information
Help  - Brings up this documentation

@{"Prefs" link "preferences"}

The preference menu options allow you to configure Control Panel to your
system, and your own likings. The settings are stored in several files in
the cp:prefs drawer except the main prefs which are stored in the s:cp.config
file.

        @{"Main" alink "prefsmain"}     - Basic CP Details
        @{"Programs" alink "prefsrest" 00} - Configure the Inet programs you use 
        @{"Options" alink "prefsrest" 10}  - Configure the options menu
        @{"Edit" alink "prefsrest" 20}     - Configure the files you wish to edit from the edit menu
        @{"Pops" alink "prefsrest" 30}     - Configure multiple pops
        @{"Amiconnect" alink "" 00}        - If Amiconnect is installed, Amiconnect will be run.

Quit  - Exits Control Panel 5

@{fg shine}@{B}@{u}OPTIONS@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

Control Panel 5 allows you to have upto 9* configurable menu items , 3 of
which also appear as buttons on the main Control Panel.

These options can be configured by using the prefs/options menu item in the
Project menu, see above.

* it is actually possible to have more menu items if you alter the
  cp:prefs/options file by hand.

@{fg shine}@{B}@{U}USERS@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

Control Panel 5 allows you to have several users using your AmiTCP setup,
the details are entered using the @{"Change User" link "ChangeUser"} buttons
and this menu option allows you to quickly select any of the configured
users.

Once selected Control Panel will alter system variables to that users
details and will also change to the Home directory of that user.

@{fg shine}@{b}@{u}POPS@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

Control Panel 5 allows you to change what PoP you use to connect to the net.
This is particularly useful for people who use companies, such as Demon,
where there are more than one PoP. As a student I live in one part of England
for the majority of the year but spend about 2 months at my parents house a
few hundred miles away, this facility makes the move a little easier.

To use this facility you firstly need to rename your current
amitcp:db/dialscript, my original dialscript is now called
amitcp:db/dialscript.London. You then need to create some new dialscript for
any other Pop you need to connect to, you can do this easily by editing your
original script and saving it under a new name, e.g.
Amitcp:db/dialscript.Leicester.

You now need to configure Control Panel 5 to use these Pops by using the
prefs/pops menu option (see above).

@{fg shine}@{b}@{u}EDIT@{fg text}@{ub}@{UU}

The edit menu allows you to edit a designated file by selecting it from the
menu, the edit menu options being configured using the prefs/edit menu item.
(see above)

You may choose what editor you wish to use by setting the env:editor
environment variable.

e.g.

Setenv Editor sys:tools/supered

@endnode

@node "Project" "Control Panel Guide - Project Menu"
@{b}@{u}Project Menu@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}About@{ub}

Show details about Control Panel 5, including your user number and my
contact details.

@{b}Help@{ub}

Brings up this documentation

@{B}Prefs@{ub}

These options open up CP5's @{"Preference" link "preferences"} editing programs
@{b}Quit@{ub}

Quits Control Panel, and saves window position is save position function is
enabled, this is the same as the End button.

@endnode

@node "logfile" "Control Panel Guide - Logfile"
@{B}@{u}Connection Log File@{ub}@{uu}

The logfile stores details about how long you have been connected to the
net, it stores this information in the same format as NComm so that
Phonebill analysing programs can be used to calculate the cost of your
calls.

The logfile can be enabled and selected by using the @{"prefs/main" link
"prefsmain"} menu item in the project menu.

@endnode
@node "statusdisplay" "Control Panel Guide - Status Display"
@{b}@{u}Status Display@{ub}@{uu}

This shows information such as the current users, user name and realname.

It also shows the current time and date, and how long you have been
connected.

The connect time will only operate when used with @{"Amiconnect" alink "Amiconnect" 0} or a modified
startnet/link script. A modified link script is included for Demon users,
other uses should add the following arexx commands to the scripts they used
to connect to the net;

Just after the command which gets your modem to dialout

Address CP5PORT "GO_CONNECTED {PopName} {Pop Phone Number}"

and just after the command which disconnect you from the net

Address CP5PORT "GO_DISCONNECTED"

This connect time will be saved to the @{"logfile" link "logfile"}.
@endnode

@node "Amiconnect" "Control Panel Guide - Amiconnect"
@{B}@{u}Amiconnect@{uu}@{ub}

This is a program which is a dialer and an Amitcp4 configuration program, it
replaces startnet,any dialler and/or link script.

It is available on aminet in the comm/tcp drawer.

@endnode

@node "CPIS" "Control Panel Guide - Control Panel Integrated Services"
@{b}@{u}Control Panel Integrated Services@{uu}@{ub}

This is a combined frontend for some of the small utilities which
can be used with AmiTCP, these utilities being ping,askhost,traceroute and
netstat.

As each of these require slightly different parameters the display changes
according to which service is currently selected.

To use this front end select the service you require using the radio buttons
and then enter any parameters required using the relevant entry boxes and
gadgets.

------------------------------------------------------------------
|                                                                |
|Select Service                   HOST NAME                      |
|                                 @{bg shine}                            @{bg back}   |
|@{fg shine}@{"o" link ""}@{fg text} Traceroute                    TRACEROUTE TIME OUT *          |
|@{fg shine}@{"o" link ""}@{fg text} Ping                          @{bg fill}              |        @{bg back}  @{bg text}   @{bg back}   |
|@{fg shine}@{"o" link ""}@{fg text} Askhost                       NETSTAT TYPE                   |
|@{fg shine}@{"o" link ""}@{fg text} Netstat                       @{bg highlight}                            @{bg back}   |
|                                                                |
|                                                                |
|                     @{"Start" link ""}             @{"Cancel" link ""}                 |
|                                                                |
------------------------------------------------------------------

* when ping selected reads NUMBER OF PING PACKETS TO SEND instead

@{" " link ""} - Normal Button
@{fg shine}@{"o" link ""}@{fg text} - Radio Button
@{bg shine}  @{bg back} - String Entry Gadget
@{bg text}  @{bg back} - Integer Entry Gadget
@{bg fill}  @{bg back} - Slider Gadget
@{bg highlight}  @{bg back} - Cycle Gadget

@endnode

@node "preferences" "Control Panel Guide - Preferences"
@{B}@{u}Preferences@{ub}@{uu}

Control Panel now has a preference editor so that you can customise the
setup more easily, than in previous versions.

The preference editor works in 5 sections these being

@{"Main" link prefsmain}     - Edits the config details CP5 needs to startup
@{"Programs" alink prefsrest 0} - Edits the details about the programs CP5 runs
@{"Options" alink prefsrest 10}  - Edits the user definable options (3 buttons 9 menus)
@{"Edit" alink prefsrest 20}     - Edits the 9 files which can be edited using the edit menu
@{"Pops" alink prefsrest 30}     - Edits the 9 possible pops

Each editor can either be started by using the options in the prefs menu, or
can be started by running the program ControlPanelPrefs with the name of the
editor you wish to use as a parameter

i.e. ControlPanelPrefs Edit  would run the edit preferences editor

If you omit the parameter the main prefs editor and then the program prefs
 editor will be run.

@endnode

@node "prefsmain" "Control Panel Guide - Main Preferences"
@{B}@{u}Main Preferences@{ub}@{uu}

This is the most complex of the editors, and is also the most important.

For the following 2 options, the @{"D" link ""} buttons will provide a
directory selector.

@{fg shine}Cp Directory@{fg text} Enter the directory where Cp5s script files are stored.

@{fg shine}AmiTCP Directory@{fg text} Enter where AmiTCP is stored

In the next 4 options the @{"F" link ""} buttons will provide a file
selector, the parameter boxes are used to enter any parameters that needs to
be passed to that program.

@{fg shine}Start AmiTCP Cmd.@{fg text} Enter the command you use to start
AmiTCP up, enter any parameters that may be needed in the adjacent box.

@{fg shine}Stop Amitcp Cmd.@{fg text} Enter the command you use to stop
Amitcp.

@{Fg shine}Connect Cmd.@{fg text} Enter the command you enter to dial your
supplier and connect to the net, may be the same as you use to start Amitcp.

@{fg shine}Disconnect Cmd.@{fg text} Enter the command you use to disconnect
from the net.


@{fg shine}Save Position@{fg text} If this is selected Cp5 will save the
position of the displays, and use these positions next time you start Cp5.
This allows for more accurate positioning.

@{fg shine}Left Offset@{fg text} If save position is not selected, this will
be the position of the left hand side of Cp5's main requester.

@{fg shine}Top Offset@{fg text} If save position is not selected, this will
be the position of the top of Cp5's main requester.

@{fg shine}Save Logfile@{fg text} Do you want a connection log to be saved.

@{fg shine}Logfile@{fg text} The filename which you want the logfile saving
as.

@{fg shine}Start AmiTCP on Startup@{fg text} If selected AmiTCP will be
started when you run CP5.

@{fg shine}Status@{fg text} This cycle gadget has three options and governs
what level of status information is displayed, the 3 levels are

No Information - No status window is opened
Limited Information - A status window detailing CP5's actions is opened
Full Information - As above but output from programs should be displayed in
an output window.

@{fg shine}Save@{fg text} Saves any changes and updates CP5 if running.

@{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text} Ignores any changes made.

@endnode

@node "prefsrest" "Control Panel Guide - Other Preferences"
@{b}@{u}Program Preferences@{ub}@{uu}

This prefs option allows you to alter the programs which CP runs, and also
allows you to enter any necessary parameters.

The left most stringbox is where you enter the program name, this can be
selected using the file selector which is accessed by the @{"F" link ""}
button. The right most box is where you enter any necessary parameters.

The initial settings are my recommended setup, the parameter setting for
Grapevine (GV) will allow the nickname setting in the change user module to
be used.

@{fg shine}Options@{fg text}

This allows you to define the user menu and button options, all options will
be displayed in the options menu and the first 3 items will also be
displayed as a button on the main display.

The left most box is the name that will appear in the menu, or on the
button. The next box is where you enter the name of the program you wish to
run from that menu, the @{"F" link ""} button will bring up a file
requester. The final box on the row is the box where you enter any
parameters that the program requires.

@{fg Shine}Edit@{fg text}

The edit menu allows you to choose files which you wish to edit, this prefs
setting allows you to add items to this menu.

The left most box is the text that will be displayed in the menu bar, the
 next box being the file you wish to edit,a file requester is available by
pressing the @{"F" link ""}.

@{fg shine}Pops @{fg text}

If you are using a service provider that has multiple Pops and are using
dialler software that uses a dialscript (amitcp:db/dialscript) , you can set up CP5 to use different
pops just by using the Pops menu.

The left most box is the name of the pop which will appear on the menu bar
and also in the control panel logfile. The next box is the filename of the
dialscript which connects you to that Pop, this shouldn't be called
amitcp:db/dialscript unless you are only using 1 Pop. The @{"F" link ""}
button can be used to bring up a file requester so that you can select the
dialscript.

@endnode

@node "Mode" "Control Panel Guide - Mini Control Panel"
@{B}@{u}Control Panel Mini Mode @{ub}@{uu}

This is the small version of the Control Panel, all the menu options are the
same as the main display but there are less buttons and no status display.
The buttons mostly relate to online activities, but e-mail and news may also be
available to those with overlaced screens.
This single strip version was requested by a registered user, and will allow
you to have a small button strip at the bottom of the screen and hence make CP
more useful when multitasking.

@{"Connect" link "connect"}@{"Disconnect" link "disconnect"}@{"FTP" link "FTP"}@{"WWW" link "WWW"}@{"Gopher" link "gopher"}@{"IRC" link "IRC"}@{"Archie" link "Archie"}@{"Telnet" link "telnet"}@{"Finger" link "finger"}@{"CPIS" link "CPIS"}@{"Mode" link "bu

@endnode

